  "passageParts": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "Happy people work differently. They’re more productive, more creative, and willing to take greater risks. And new research suggests that happiness might influence\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nfirms work, too. Companies located in places with happier people invest more, according to a recent research paper.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 2
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​, firms in happy places spend more on R&D (research and development). That’s because happiness is linked to the kind of longer-term thinking\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nfor making investments for the future. The researchers wanted to know if the\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 4
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nand inclination for risk-taking that come with happiness would\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 5
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthe way companies invested. So they compared U.S. cities’ average happiness\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 6
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nby Gallup polling with the investment activity of publicly traded firms in those areas.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 7
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nenough, firms’ investment and R&D intensity were correlated with the happiness of the area in which they were\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 8
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​. But is it really happiness that’s linked to investment, or could something else about happier cities\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 9
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nwhy firms there spend more on R&D? To find out, the researchers controlled for various\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 10
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthat might make firms more likely to invest—like size, industry, and sales—and for indicators that a place was\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 11
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto live in, like growth in wages or population. The link between happiness and investment generally\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 12
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\neven after accounting for these things. The correlation between happiness and investment was particularly strong for younger firms, which the authors\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 13
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto “less codified decision making process” and the possible presence of “younger and less\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 14
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nmanagers who are more likely to be influenced by sentiment.” The relationship was\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 15
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nstronger in places where happiness was spread more\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 16
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​. Firms seem to invest more in places where most people are relatively happy, rather than in places with happiness inequality.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthis doesn’t prove that happiness causes firms to invest more or to take a longer-term view, the authors believe it at least\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nat that possibility. It’s not hard to imagine that local culture and sentiment would help\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nhow executives think about the future. “It surely seems plausible that happy people would be more forward-thinking and creative and\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nR&D more than the average,” said one researcher."
    }
  ],
